{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c879ce71-5ff3-4537-9e68-bafb8490d753","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes without `createdump`, you have two main options:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` crash reports in:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These contain the stack trace, exception type, and faulting address. Open them with Console.app or any text editor.\n\n2. **Core dumps via `lldb`** — You can attach `lldb` and generate a core dump manually:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ./MyApp  # run until crash\n   ```\n   Core files land in `/cores/` (if enabled via `kern.coredump` sysctl).\n\n3. **Enable core dumps if disabled:**\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n**Tip:** The `.ips` files in `DiagnosticReports` are usually the fastest path — they're generated automatically with no setup required.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5504fecb-c126-41f2-9806-f65c5a2cbb71","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":305,"requestId":"F880:1E9F:4CA38A9:54E226B:69F9FFE4"},"id":"27c31580-e3dd-4f2d-ab62-805975a38c2a","timestamp":"2026-05-05T14:34:19.962Z","parentId":"bd57aa65-03ee-4da5-8c1c-873a2248b14b"}
